{{Quote|Frankly, the entire concept of midi-chlorians is unclear to us.|[[Wil Jhonems]], marketing manager|<ref name="HNN50">{{HoloNetNewsWeb|50|jediwatch/1344_2.html|Jedi TradeChips Spark Controversy}}</ref>}}
'''Spotts TradeChip Company''' was a manufacturer of collectible [[tradechip]]s during the latter days of the [[Galactic Republic/Legends|Galactic Republic]], headquartered in the [[Jrade District/Legends|Jrade District]] on [[Coruscant/Legends|Coruscant]].

While most of their tradechips depicted [[Smashball/Legends|smashball]], [[Limmie/Legends|bolo-ball]], and [[Podracing/Legends|podracing]] stars, they produced one controversial line of [[Jedi TradeChips]] in [[22 BBY/Legends|22 BBY]] depicting famous members of the [[Jedi Order/Legends|Jedi Order]]. Much like their sports chips, this line of tradechips generated small [[Hologram/Legends|holograms]] of the Jedi in question, and contained a short biography and statistics (such as planet of origin, midi-chlorian count, and number of confirmed kills.)

[[Jedi Master/Legends|Jedi Master]] [[Coleman Trebor/Legends|Coleman Trebor]] spoke out to [[HoloNet News/Legends|HoloNet News]] against the tradechips, and attempted to stop their distribution. This was partly because the Order considered merchandising the Jedi to "dishonor the nature of [[The Force/Legends|the Force]]", and partly because the information on the tradechips was often wildly inaccurate (for example, misidentifying [[Yoda/Legends|Yoda]] as a [[Lannik (species)/Legends|Lannik]], and giving him an incorrect [[Midi-chlorian/Legends|midi-chlorian]] count of four million.)

[[Wil Jhonems]], Spotts' marketing manager, disagreed, pointing out that the Jedi were better role models for children during the troubled times of the [[Separatist Crisis/Legends|Separatist Crisis]] than professional athletes. He also defended the inaccuracy of the tradechip statistics, pointing out that Spotts used the best information available without access to the library of the [[Jedi Archives/Legends|Jedi Archives]].

==Behind the scenes==
Spotts is a near-anagram for [[Topps]], a trading card company which has published several lines of ''Star Wars'' trading cards.

The unreliable information given by the tradechips, especially the misidentification of Yoda's species and the number given for his midi-chlorian count, may be an oblique reference to the notoriously inaccurate fansite run by [[Fanon|SuperShadow]]. SuperShadow also quoted four million as Yoda's midi-chlorian count, although he listed Yoda as a [[Whills|Whill]] and not a Lannik.

